6469<div>

6470<h3 class="subHdr">

6471Engineered for Beautiful Durability</h3>

6472

6473

6474<p class="bodyCopy">

6475Dekton is a combination of glass, porcelain, quartz, and other natural materials. Using advanced technology along with intense heat and pressure, the result is a product that has all the beauty of natural stone, but with stronger properties. Dekton has a high resistance to heat, scratches, stains, freezing, and thawing. The surface is non-porous, meaning there&#39;s little to no water absorption. The engineering process results in larger pieces, providing you with a countertop that doesn&#39;t require joints or seams. It&#39;s available in three textures. XGloss features a highly polished sheen. UItratexture provides a natural look, capturing the beauty of textures such as wood, slate, or marble. Ultramatte has a matte finish for a softer appearance. Overall, Dekton is a great material to use indoors or outdoors, including kitchens, bathrooms, islands, and bar tops.</p>

7338<h3 class="subHdr">

7339Supercharged Quartz</h3>

7340

7341

7342<p class="bodyCopy">

7343Silestone is crafted from over 94% natural quartz to create a gorgeous, non-porous countertop option. Since quartz is one of the most sturdy materials around, Silestone is resistant to stains from coffee, wine, olive oil, makeup, and other substances that tend to mar surfaces. On top of over 90 colors, there are also three unique textures to choose from. Go with Polished for richer, high-shine colors. Select Volcano for a rugged finish that adds notes of texture. Opt for Suede for a velvety look that&rsquo;s also soft and smooth to the touch. With its tough composition, Silestone is a great option for both kitchens and bathrooms.</p>

8148<h3 class="subHdr">

8149Gorgeous Granite</h3>

8150

8151

8152<p class="bodyCopy">

8153Sensa is different from other granites because it features a specialized protective coating that provides stain resistance as well as protection against UV rays. This coating is also Greenguard certified, meaning it&rsquo;s safe for direct contact with food. Each slab is unique, naturally sourced with special attention to finding the most beautiful colors and veining so you have a one-of-a-kind style in your home. Cleaning is as easy as using water and a non-abrasive soap, keeping worktops germ-free and beautiful. Sensa combines the benefits of natural stone with technology to make it more durable.</p>

8951<div>

8952<h3 class="subHdr">

8953Highly Personalized For Your Space</h3>

8954

8955

8956<p class="bodyCopy">

8957The Natural Stone collection features a variety of materials including marble, travertine, granite, limestone, and more. These slabs are sourced from around the world to provide gorgeous, completely natural surfaces to enhance the beauty of your home. Each type of stone and slab has its own unique characteristics, strengths, and features. All are fire and heat resistant, as well as resistant to UV rays which keeps the coloring consistent over time. Natural Stone brings a unique touch that can&#39;t be replicated.</p>

9747<h2 class="hdr normal textCenter" style="text-align: center;">

9748What Types of Countertops Are There?</h2>

9749

9750

9751<p style="text-align: center;">

9752There are quite a few options for countertops. Each has their pros and cons, but take a look and see which you gravitate to most.</p>

9753

9754</div>

9755</div>

9756</div>

9757</div>

9758<div class="">

9759<div class="styles-plugin-outer custom-outer-style-ROW-afb-fc-b-abe-eeee">

9760<div class="styles-plugin-inner custom-inner-style-ROW-afb-fc-b-abe-eeee">

9761<div class="Row-module_global__1T17H merce-row-container">

9762<div class="Layout-module_row__3IzXF merce-row">

9763<div class="Layout-module_omnimerse-column-sm-4__3eiub Layout-module_marginTopOnSmall__2rO47 merce-column">

9764<div class="">

9765<div class="styles-plugin-inner custom-inner-style-COLUMN-eed-da-d-bb-cbcc">

9766<div class="merce-column-container">

9767<div class="styles-plugin-inner custom-inner-style-TEXTBLOCK--ac-eb-db-abeedf">

9768<div>

9769<div class=" TextBlock-module_textBlockContainer__X2cPA">

9770<div>

9771<p class="subHdr">

9772Quartz</p>

9773

9774</div>

9775</div>

9776</div>

9777</div>

9778<div class="styles-plugin-inner custom-inner-style-SINGLE_IMAGE-a-eb--b-abfacddfc">

9779<div class="SingleImage-module_singleImage__3fWXf a-eb--b-abfacddfc-singleImageAlignment">

9780<img class="a-eb--b-abfacddfc-image" src="https://img.vevano.com/iLWBgZKjoq7R06hPLNWIV8yayPJMZqW-2AN2rECJD3s/rs:fill:0:132/q:80/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdG9yYWdlLmdvb2dsZWFwaXMuY29tL3ZldmFuby1hc3NldHMvY29zZW50aW5vL2NvdW50ZXJ0b3BRdWFydHouanBn" alt="quartz" title="quartz"/>

9781</div>

9782</div>

9783<div class="styles-plugin-inner custom-inner-style-TEXTBLOCK-ada-f--ab-fedf">

9784<div>

9785<div class=" TextBlock-module_textBlockContainer__X2cPA">

9786<div>

9787<p class="bodyCopy">

9788Technically an engineered stone, quartz combines with other natural materials to create an incredibly sturdy countertop. Thanks to its resilience, its popularity is growing in both kitchens and bathrooms. Unlike granite, quartz is a non-porous surface, giving it a natural resistance to staining, scratches, and heat without the need for sealant. Thanks to a bonding process that involves high temperatures and intense pressure, quartz is also impact resistant.</p>

9807Granite</p>

9809</div>

9815<img class="bbfc--d-ae-cfbfa-image" src="https://img.vevano.com/X-mQpdGSRVyUJ6fpVsFl0KgbqStUv9mNdJxqWYuUjiU/rs:fill:0:132/q:80/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdG9yYWdlLmdvb2dsZWFwaXMuY29tL3ZldmFuby1hc3NldHMvY29zZW50aW5vL2NvdW50ZXJ0b3BHcmFuaXRlLmpwZw" alt="granite" title="granite"/>

9821<div>

9822<p class="bodyCopy">

9823A natural stone known for both beauty and durability, granite is a popular choice for countertops in kitchens or bathrooms. It&rsquo;s durable, resistant to both heat and scratches. Since granite is a porous material, seal it regularly to maintain its stain resistance. It&rsquo;s also considered an upgrade, so it adds value to your home. A wide variety of colors and veining are available in granite, making it easy to personalize your look.</p>

9841<p class="subHdr">

9842Marble</p>

9843

9844</div>

9856<div>

9857<p class="bodyCopy">

9858A gorgeous natural stone, marble is a luxurious add-on that other countertop types often try to mimic. Marble is also a favorite among bakers and chocolatiers given its resistance to temperature changes, so it&rsquo;s a good choice for foodies and bakers. Like granite, it&rsquo;s a porous material and requires regular sealing to avoid staining. Given that it&rsquo;s a luxury, marble not only adds value to a home, but elevates the ambience of your space as well.</p>

9887Dekton</p>

9891</div>

9900<div class=" TextBlock-module_textBlockContainer__X2cPA">

9901<div>

9902<p class="bodyCopy">

9903An engineered material, Dekton fuses natural stone, porcelain, and ceramic together through heat and pressure to create a material that&rsquo;s more durable than many stone types. Dekton inherently has high resistance to heat, acids, oils, and freezing temperatures, making it a great option for indoor or outdoor use. Since it is a man-made material, the options for looks and design are varied. It&rsquo;s available in high gloss, matte, or can even look like slate, marble, or wood.</p>

9922Laminate</p>

9936<div>

9937<p class="bodyCopy">

9938Created from layers of particleboard, resins, plastic, and a photo layer, laminate is a cost-effective option that works well in kitchens. Installation is easy, lighter than stone, with pieces made to order after measuring. Designs are flexible, available in solid colors, stone textures, and others. While not as durable as stone and highly susceptible to heat, it is easy to maintain with soap and water.</p>

9957Natural Stone</p>

9972<p class="bodyCopy">

9973Natural stone options include soapstone, limestone, travertine, and others. They are typically resistant to heat, though each type of stone has its own unique properties. Cleaning is easy, consisting of pH neutral soap and water. Natural stone is a great way to add personalization and luxury to a space. Colors, textures, and veining vary, but one thing is for sure: it&#39;s beautiful.</p>

10018Not just for backsplashes and flooring, tile is a sturdy surface for countertops. With how many styles and types of tile there are, there are endless possibilities when it comes to styling, personalization, and design. Cleaning the tile itself is easy, it&rsquo;s the grout lines that require more attention.</p>

10052<p class="bodyCopy">

10053With high durability, concrete is another countertop option. Concrete is usually mixed on-site ands once it sets it&rsquo;s incredibly heavy. While offering quite an array of styles, polishes, and design potential, concrete requires regular upkeep. Wipe up spills immediately, and frequently seal and wax counters to prevent stains and damage.</p>

10086<div>

10087<p class="bodyCopy">

10088Adding a natural element to any kitchen or bar area, butcher block works especially well with painted cabinets. Use it either sealed or unsealed, though if it&rsquo;s sealed it&rsquo;s best not to prep food directly on the surface, whereas unsealed can lead to scratched surfaces. It&rsquo;s a cost-effective option compared to stone, but since wood is porous, clean up spills right away to prevent damage.</p>

10148<div>

10149<h2 class="hdr normal">

10150Caring for Countertops</h2>

10151

10152

10153<p class="bodyCopy">

10154Each type of countertop material has its own maintenance schedule. There&rsquo;s regular maintenance, special routines, stain treatments, and possible repairs.</p>

10155

10156

10157<p class="bodyCopy">

10158As a quick note, most stone countertops are easy to clean with water and a non-abrasive cleanser. Even with stain resistant materials, we recommend cleaning a spill as soon as possible to make sure your counters stay beautiful for years to come.</p>

10159

10160

10161<p class="bodyCopy">

10162For more information and specifics for each type of stone, see our <a href="https://vevano.com/resource-center/care-for-stone-countertops">

10163article on stone maintenance.</a>

10164</p>

10165

10210<h2 class="hdr normal">

10211Which Countertop is Best for Kitchens?</h2>

10212

10213

10214<p class="bodyCopy">

10215Since kitchens are such high traffic areas in the home, countertop material matters. When considering a countertop for your kitchen, it&rsquo;s helpful to prioritize functionality, aesthetics, and budget as each can help guide you on which material and style will best suit your space.</p>

10216

10217

10218<p class="bodyCopy">

10219Generally speaking, granite, marble, quartz, and solid surfaces such as Dekton are all popular choices for kitchens. Each has a multitude of colors, finishes, and thickness to find the ideal match for your space. Even though Dekton is an engineered stone, there are colors and textures available that look like marble, granite, or quartz, even wood-like styles as well.</p>

10220

10221

10222<p class="bodyCopy">

10223How this countertop fits in with your daily routine is a major consideration. With butcher block, concrete, and marble, extra care is needed on a regular basis, particularly when it comes to spills. Dekton, granite, tile, and quartz, on the other hand, are more forgiving when it comes to heat, scratches, and spills. Laminate lies somewhere in between. It&rsquo;s resistant to spills and cleans easily, but heat damages laminate quickly.</p>

10224

10225

10226<p class="bodyCopy">

10227When it comes to cost, butcher block and laminate are the most affordable options, though they don&rsquo;t add to the value of your home. Tile is also a cost-saving option, depending on the style and whether you install it yourself. Stone materials such as quartz, granite, marble add value and tend to last longer than laminate or butcher block, given the natural strength and properties inherent with stone.</p>

10228

10303<h2 class="hdr normal">

10304Which Countertop is Best for Bathrooms?</h2>

10305

10306

10307<p class="bodyCopy">

10308Much like choosing a countertop for your kitchen, choosing one for a bathroom depends on your priorities when it comes to style, function, and budget. With bathrooms, function includes withstanding the variations in humidity and temperature, particularly in bathrooms with showers.</p>

10309

10310

10311<p class="bodyCopy">

10312For powder rooms, nearly any material works well including butcher block, laminate, stone, and solid surfaces. From there it&rsquo;s a matter of what your preferences and needs are as far as style, size, and budget are concerned.</p>

10313

10314

10315<p class="bodyCopy">

10316For primary bathrooms and larger bathrooms with baths and showers, stone countertops offer long term durability against the varying temperatures and moisture.</p>
